covered: Valid Request Scenarios: Default pagination (TC01), pagination with offset/limit (TC02), and audit variants (TC03, TC04, TC19, TC20) cover typical successful fetch paths.
Pagination coverage: Scenarios cover standard pagination (offset/limit) (TC02, TC05), empty results (TC06, TC07), boundary conditions (TC11, TC16), and partially populated data (TC21).
Audit parameter coverage: FULL, MINIMAL, and NONE (implicit) audit cases are tested (TC03, TC04, TC19, TC20).
Error handling: Tests for invalid pagination parameters (TC08, TC09), invalid audit (TC10), limit bounds (TC11, TC16), unauthorized (TC12), and system failure (TC13) are included.
Edge cases: Extra unexpected parameters (TC15) and very large integer boundary tests (TC16).
Performance: Under normal load (TC17) and peak load with concurrency (TC18).
State variation: Partially populated database scenario (TC21).
Regression coverage: Backward compatibility with missing audit param (TC20) and MINIMAL with offset 0 (TC19).
gaps: Caching behavior: No tests validating caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or cache invalidation.
Rate limiting: No tests for throttling or 429 responses under high request rate.
Authorization depth: No explicit 403 forbidden scenario for insufficient privileges beyond 401.
Type validation: No tests for non-integer parameter types (e.g., offset=abc).
recommendations: Add tests to verify caching headers in responses (ETag/Cache-Control) and behavior when data changes.
Introduce rate-limiting tests to ensure 429 responses or throttling behavior under concurrent requests.
Add a 403 forbidden test path to cover insufficient permissions with valid authentication.
Add tests for non-integer or malformed query parameter types (e.g., offset=abc, limit=xyz) to confirm proper 400/422 responses.
Consider expanding coverage for content-type and response headers, and more aggressive concurrency scenarios.
